YES! YES! YES! Okay so this place has no thrills! It is super basic. Walking in I knew exactly what to expect. Those things included, basic service if any at all and the bare minimum. Honey found this place online and wanted to give it a try based on reviews. I decided to join him since I had driven past this place a few times and though it is in a rough part of town I was intrigued; that's usually where the best places are.  We walked in on a Sunday afternoon, grabbed drinks out of the fridge and sat down. A young lady walked over, handed us menus, and asked us if we needed a minute, to which we said we did. For my drink I went with a Country Club soda! I am not really a soda drinker but it is the soda of my country and I do not come across it often. They had the raspberry flavor which is the red one, I really love the light orange flavor called merengue but they didn't have it. Honey chose a coke! Both of our drinks were in the glass bottle and his definitely came from Mexico! Some people might not really care but there truly is a difference in flavor. Honey ordered himself a combination of carnitas and al pastor tacos, he enjoyed both kinds. I ordered 1 carnitas and 1 chorizo, they were both good but the carnitas tacos was delicious!!! Next time I will get both carnitas! The sauces they bring to your table are delicious as well- the red packs a kick but the green is just plain delicious!  After we were done eating we walked up to the register and paid. This is actually kind of a small grocery store (with not much but sodas and candies from south America) and then the restaurant in the back. Our tacos were $2.25 a piece, while a bit small they were delicious.  I will definitely be back here. I can honestly say this is the best taco I have had in Tampa and also the closest to the real thing (believe me I was just in Mexico less than 2 months ago).  Give it a try! Just keep in mind you are there for the food- not the service- not the ambience- etc.  There was ample parking when we got there since it is in a plaza with a some doctors offices that seem closed on the weekends. While Miguel's just up the road is a nice upper scale Mexican food experience this is a lot closer to the real deal. Just keep going straight down on MacDill past Miguel's and you cannot miss it!

I'm pretty picky with my Mexican food. Acapulco definitely has some good eats, but it's not the best I've had. The ingredients in the tacos were great the steak and chorizo were flavorful, but the tortilla was so-so - it could've tasted better and it tasted cold which was off putting.  I did like that they gave you plenty of limes and sauces. That's definitely a plus.  The cilantro and onion toppings were pretty much your value worth for $2. I didn't feel like it was a great deal or anything. I would've honestly preferred a double tortilla taco.  The refried beans were okay. Thankfully they weren't too greasy. Still not my favorite.  The horchata was the biggest letdown. It was overly milky and sweet. There was no powdery or grit taste, but it still wasn't to my liking.  The service was okay. The waitress tried to be a little friendlier in the second half of my visit, but everyone there looked annoyed to have customers so overall it wasn't a great experience.  I would go back here, but I think I'd rather try out some new places in the future.
